{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489100"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:04:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:04:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"591"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"591","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/591"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0,0.27,0.58,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"591"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56599"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"591","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/591"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"591"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42143"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"176"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1376"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2685"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11188"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17479"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17484"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17523"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18967"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19946"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30193"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44255"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56599","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/56599"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old man is referred to a haematology clinic following an incidental finding of increased globulins on liver function testing (LFT). His GP orders annual complete blood exams and LFTs due to his excessive alcohol consumption of six standard drinks per day, despite repeated attempts by his GP to encourage him to reduce his drinking. He denies any history of bony pain, fatigue, infections or easy bruising/bleeding. The examination is unremarkable, with no evidence of lymphadenopathy, hepatosplenomegaly or bony tenderness. His blood work is as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBiochemistry\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EElectrolytes normal\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGlobulins 56 g/L (high)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBilirubin 18 \u00b5mol/L (\u0026lt;21)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGGT 85 U/L (\u0026lt;60)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EALP 100 U/L (30-130)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EALT 70 U/L (\u0026lt;40)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAST 180 U/L (\u0026lt;40)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EeGFR 120 mL/min\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EProtein Electrophoresis\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIgG Paraprotein detected: 7 g/L\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaematology\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHb 135 g/L (125-155)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWCC 5 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (4-11)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelets 300 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (150-450)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of this picture?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Multiple myeloma","Renal failure","Chronic alcohol hepatitis","Monoclonal gammopathy of undetermined significance (MGUS)","Myelodysplasia"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMultiple myeloma\u003C/strong\u003E is a plasma cell dyscrasia. Often patients will present with signs or symptoms related to plasma cell infiltration into bone or other organs, or light chain disease resulting in renal failure. Anaemia, bony pain, renal failure, fatigue, hypercalcaemia, and weight loss may be seen. Rarely, hepatosplenomegaly, lymphadenopathy and fever can also be seen. The diagnosis of Myeloma usually consists of a monoclonal gammopathy or light chain ratio elevation, the presence of CRAB features (Hypercalcaemia, Renal Impairment, Anaemia and Bone Involvement) and plasmacytosis (\u0026gt;10%) on bone marrow biopsy. Newer international diagnostic criteria include three \u0027Myeloma Defining Events\u0027 which are a Serum Free Light Chain Ratio of 100 or more, Bone Marrow Clonal Plasmacytosis of 60% or more, and \u0026gt;1 focal lesion of 5mm or more on MRI imaging.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMyelodysplasia\u003C/strong\u003E, or the myelodysplastic syndromes, is a group of malignant stem cell disorders. It often manifests with pancytopenia from impaired cell production on blood counts eg, anaemia, neutropaenia, thrombocytopenia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERenal failure\u003C/strong\u003E and iron deficiency are unlikely given this patient\u0027s normal blood counts and renal function. The mild LFT derangement is likely secondary to \u003Cstrong\u003Echronic alcohol use\u003C/strong\u003E however this would not explain the raised paraprotein levels or globulins.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile the patient has had excessive alcohol consumption, \u003Cstrong\u003Echronic alcohol hepatitis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with elevated liver enzymes, particularly AST and ALT, and may be associated with jaundice and hepatomegaly. However, it does not typically cause an isolated increase in globulins or the presence of a paraprotein, which suggests a monoclonal gammopathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMonoclonal gammopathy\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Eof undetermined significance (MGUS)\u003C/strong\u003E is, importantly in this case, an asymptomatic potential premalignant disorder defined by the presence of a serum monoclonal protein at a concentration \u0026lt;30g/L without any CRAB features or bone marrow plasmacytosis. Depending on multiple factors, patients with MGUS carry the potential to develop multiple myeloma and therefore regular monitoring is required. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAs an aside, if there is bone marrow plasmacytosis of 10-60% or a Paraprotein \u0026gt;30g/L AND no evidence of CRAB features, \u003Cstrong\u003ESmouldering Myeloma\u003C/strong\u003E would be the diagnosis. There is not enough information in this question to differentiate between smouldering myeloma and MGUS, as a bone marrow biopsy is needed.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The presence of a serum IgG paraprotein (or M-protein) \u003C30g/L should always raise the possibility of a monoclonal gammopathy or Myeloma."],"references":["Eslick R, Talaulikar D. Multiple myeloma: from diagnosis to treatment. AFP. 2013; 42(10) 684-688."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42143"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"591"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42143","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/42143"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-21T07:34:28+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-21T07:35:08+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"591"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56599"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":